<subSubSection id="C34F6533993144610782FD087978FCAA" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BEA36B8993144610782FD087978FCAA" blockId="8.[151,1437,389,848]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis id="B921EAAA993144610782FD087A5DFD65" bold="true" box="[199,335,713,740]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Comments.</emphasis>
This species may be the corresponding female of 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D3B9931446104C4FD0B7F02FD62" authorityName="Lanes &amp; Azevedo" authorityYear="2004" box="[897,1040,713,740]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis id="B921EAAA9931446104C4FD0B7F02FD62" box="[897,1040,713,740]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">A. singularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species described based on male specimens only. Both species are abundant in the Amazon region and due to their sympatric occurrence, this hypothesis should be tested with molecular data.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
